        <p>Rabdentse Ruins, located in West Sikkim near Pelling, hold historical significance as the second capital of the former Kingdom of Sikkim between 1670 and 1814. Overlooking scenic views of the Kanchenjunga mountain range, this site is a testament to the ancient kingdom’s rich cultural and architectural heritage. Once a vibrant palace complex, it was destroyed during a Nepalese invasion in the early 19th century, leaving behind ruins that echo stories of Sikkim's royal past. The Archaeological Survey of India has preserved the site, and visitors can now walk through the remnants of royal residences, prayer halls, and courtyards, surrounded by a serene landscape that offers both historical insight and natural beauty.</p>
